items.author: Associated Press

items.title: LIVE: Rally against South Korean President Yoon after his impeachment
items.author: Associated Press
items.content:

items.title: United 'fantasy flight' takes kids to the 'North Pole' at Denver airport
items.author: Associated Press
items.content:
Dozens of kids cheered on a festively decked-out plane in Denver on Saturday when the pilot announced their destination for the day: the North Pole. For more than 30 years, United Airlines has been staging its annual “fantasy flights” to fictional North Poles at airports around the world to bring holiday cheer to children and their families. (AP video by Thomas Peipert)

The children, some of whom have serious health struggles, were taken on a roughly 45-minute flight near the city before landing back at Denver International Airport and being towed to a hangar transformed by United Airlines employees and volunteers into the North Pole.

items.title: LIVE: Pope Francis arrives in Corsica, France
items.author: Associated Press
items.content:
Pope Francis arrives in Corsica two days before his 88th birthday. Francis’ one-day trip to capital Ajaccio, birthplace of Napoleon, is the first papal visit to the French island and will include a meeting with French President Emmanuel Macron. Read more here: https://bit.ly/3Dhu9Y5

#popefrancis #france #live

items.title: Palestinians in Syria's Yarmouk camp hope they can return and rebuild their homes
items.author: Associated Press
items.content:
Following the toppling of the Syrian government residents of the Yarmouk camp outside Damascus, which had housed much of the Palestinian diaspora since 1957, are beginning to return to homes they fled. While much was heavily damaged by government bombardment, many are thinking about rebuilding their houses and coming back for good. (AP Video by Malak Harb) Read more here: https://bit.ly/4fnQWi2

items.title: Activists release 'undercover' images of foxes at Finnish fur farms to push for EU ban of trade
items.author: Associated Press
items.content:
Finnish advocacy group Oikeutta Elaimille and Humane Society International have released images taken from an “undercover investigation” at three fur farms which they say shows the behind-the-scenes realities of the fur trade. But fur farming group FIFUR said the images were "selective", and that the industry has the "highest welfare standards of any form of animal husbandry."

items.title: What happens next in South Korea?
items.author: Associated Press
items.content:
Following a parliament vote to impeach President Yoon Suk Yeol, South Korea's opposition leader urged the Constitutional Court to rule swiftly on a bid to remove him from office. But Korea Univeristy Law Professor Chang Young-soo says there is only a "50-50 chance" of Yoon being removed.

items.title: One week into a new Syria, rebels aim for normalcy and Syrians enjoy new-found sense of freedom
items.author: Associated Press
items.content:
On Sunday, people went about their lives as usual in Syria's capital, with schools and universities opening their doors for students after a week of closure. While the economy is in tatters, poverty is widespread, and inflation and unemployment are high, in this moment of flux, many are ready to feel out the way ahead.

(AP video shot by Ghaith AlSayed and Abdulrahman Shaheen)

items.title: Powerful cyclone makes landfall in Mozambique and Mayotte after sweeping across Indian Ocean
items.author: Associated Press
items.content:
At least 11 people have died after Cyclone Chido caused devastating damage in the French territory of Mayotte in the Indian Ocean, while footage from the UN Children's Fund (UNICEF) showed destroyed boats washed up on the beachfront of Pemba, Mozambique.

items.title: WATCH: Santa runs take place across the world
items.author: Associated Press
items.content:
Residents in cities across the world dressed as Santa Claus and ran in races as a part of the annual tradition leading up to Christmas.

Thousands took part in the races in locations including Hungary, France, Mexico and Kosovo.
